                        <interp inst="t18280410-249-victim1384" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                  ; and fixed to a certain building of his; against the Statute
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-249-person1385">
                  CHARLES 
                  GOODMAN
               <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1385" type="surname" value="GOODMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1385" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1385" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman, of Islington. I was on duty, on the 7th of April, between three and four o'clock in the morning; I heard the spring of a rattle, and the cry of Stop thief! I saw the prisoner running in Cloudesley-square, and took him; I asked him what was amiss - he said, "There is nothing amiss; let me go." I took him to the watch-house; and these two files were found on him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-249-person1386">
                  CHARLES 
                  LEWIS
               <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1386" type="surname" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1386" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1386" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman. I was on duty on the night in question, in Chapman-street, and saw the prisoner in the road, with this glass in a handkerchief, under his arm; I asked him where he was going - he said he came from Highgate. I told him he must come with me to the watch-house; he threw down the glass, and broke every pane of it - he then bolted. I pursued him, and sprung my rattle.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-249-person1387">
                  JAMES 
                  THOMPSON
               <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1387" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1387" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-249-person1387" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman. I was near Lewis, and saw him stop the prisoner - I was going to him, and saw him throw down the glass, which I took up; this is it - I saw the prisoner searched, and these files found.</p>
               <p>JOSEPH ELLIOTT. My brother's name, is John Elliott; he is building a house for a gentleman at <placeName id="t18280410-249-crimeloc1326">Islington</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-249-crimeloc1326" type="placeName" value="Islington"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-249-crimeloc1326" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-249-off1324 t18280410-249-crimeloc1326"></join> - and I was at work there; I left these two files in the house, on the Saturday evening - I particularly fastened the house up; the house had been entered, by forcing in the sashes, which were only tacked in - I suppose this glass was in the frames; but it is all broken now - the glass was gone from the frames.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182804100112"></xptr>Prisoner's Defence. I picked up the glass and files by the side of a wall.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280410-249-verdict1327" type="verdictDescription">
